Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /supˈpiː.loː/, [sʊpˈpiː.ɫ̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /supˈpi.lo/, [supˈpiː.lɔ]

Etymology 1[edit]

sub- + a -pīlō element as in compīlō (“I rob, pillage, or steal from”)

Alternative forms[edit]

  • subpīlō, suppeilō

Verb[edit]

suppīlō (present infinitive suppīlāre, perfect active suppīlāvī, supine suppīlātum); first conjugation

  1. (construed with the accusative of thing and dative of person) I steal stealthily, I filch, I pilfer, I purloin
  2. (construed with the accusative of person) I rob (someone) without being noticed, I strip, I pluck, I fleece

Etymology 2[edit]

suppīlō¹ (verb) +‎ -ō (suffix forming masculine agent nouns)

Alternative forms[edit]

Noun[edit]

suppīlō m (genitive suppīlōnis); third declension

  1. one who steals or robs stealthily, a thief
